## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort()` kills a thread that exceeds a time limit. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Why it breaks

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 behavior |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### The fundamental shift

.NET Framework used **preemptive** cancellation — the runtime forcibly injected `ThreadAbortException` into the thread. Modern .NET requires **cooperative** cancellation — the work must voluntarily check a `CancellationToken` and stop itself.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async overload (preferred)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowComputation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must accept and honor the token
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        // Check token at regular intervals in your work
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            // ... do a chunk of work ...
        }
        return finalResult;
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---|---|
| **Work ignores the token** — cancellation never actually stops it | Insert `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints in loops and between expensive operations |
| **`Thread.Sleep` blocks ignoring token** | Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` |
| **Token not forwarded through call chain** | Every method in the chain must accept and pass the `CancellationToken` |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using` — it holds timers and callbacks |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. If work has long gaps between checks, cancellation is delayed |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you can't modify the work to check a token, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` — there is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` |

### What was removed and why

| Removed | Reason | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run` is lighter and uses the thread pool | `Task.Run(() => work(token), token)` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ | `cts.Cancel()` (automatic via `CancelAfter`) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in modern .NET | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` to decide whether to continue |
